 such as: Should all green organisms be considered plants? Why do these organisms look the way they do? How are they related to one another and to other chlorophyll-free organisms? How do they reproduce? How have they changed and diversified over time? And how has the presence of green organisms changed the Earth’s ecosystems? More engaging than a traditional textbook and displaying an astonishing breadth, How the Earth Turned Green will both delight and enlighten embryonic botanists and any student interested in the evolutionary history of plants.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBotany. 0aPlantsxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aplant, green, greenery, botany, biology, history of plants, herbarium, biological sciences, organisms, chlorophyll, diversity, earth, planet, evolutionary framework, evolution, reproduction, diversification, ecosystems, embryonic botanist, algae, fossils, ferns, bacteria, moss, conifers, ginkgoes, ecology, classification, phytology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226069807423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226069807/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles